<article>
	<header>
	<h1><a href="http://foodsense.is/blog/mark-bittmans-baked-broccoli-rabe">Mark Bittman&#8217;s Baked Broccoli Rabe</a></h1>
		</header>
		
	<div class="group">
		<img src="http://foodsense.is/uploads/post-images/BroccoliRabe_Blog.jpg" class="post-image border" alt="image" />			<p>I could tell you how easy it is to make this simple and lovely side dish. But I think it&#8217;d be better if you clicked through to <a href="http://dinersjournal.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/11/the-minimalist-baked-broccoli-rabe-with-parmesan/">Mark Bittman&#8217;s video</a>. </p>

<p>His recipe for baked broccoli rabe lends itself to any greens; you can try it with spinach, kale, broccoli. And, while his recipe calls for parmesean, you can use the <a href="http://www.galaxyfoods.com/galaxy-products/vegan-cheese/vegan/">vegan version</a>, or some nutritional yeast to make this recipe dairy free.</p>

<p><small>Photo: flickr member <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/cbertel/2876442206/sizes/l/in/photostream/">cbertel</a></p><p></small></p>
			</div>
		
